<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-summary">
    <title>Summary</title>

<p>
    This chapter introduced the fundamental ideas of sampling theory and statistical estimation. 
    These concepts explain how information obtained from a sample can be used to make inferences 
    about an entire population. Throughout the chapter, R-Instat was used to demonstrate how these 
    concepts can be explored using real datasets and interactive dialogs.
</p>

<p>
    The main topics covered in this chapter include:
    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                Populations, samples, and different sampling methods (<xref ref="sec-srs"/>).
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Sampling theory, including the law of large numbers, sampling distributions, 
                and the Central Limit Theorem (<xref ref="sec-lawlargenumbers"/>, <xref ref="sec-samplesandclt"/>).
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Estimating population parameters using sample statistics, 
                including the sample mean and sample standard deviation (<xref ref="sec-pointestimates"/>).
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Confidence intervals, their interpretation, and how they quantify the uncertainty associated with 
                statistical estimates (<xref ref="sec-ci"/>).
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</p>

<p>
    Along the way, you learned how to use R-Instat to import datasets from the <c>lsrdata</c> package, 
    calculate descriptive statistics using the
    <c>Describe &gt; One Variable &gt; Summarise...</c> dialog, and interpret confidence intervals using the
    <c>Describe &gt; Two/Three Variables &gt; Correlations...</c> dialog.
</p>

<p>
    The methods presented in this chapter provide the foundation for statistical inference. In the chapters that follow, 
    these ideas will be extended to hypothesis testing, regression, and other statistical methods, all of which rely on the 
    principles of sampling and estimation introduced here.
</p>
</section>